Here is an example of how you can create a simple search bar using PHP and HTML:

**index.php**
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        #search-bar {
            width: 50%;
            height: 30px;
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Search Bar</h1>
    <form action="search.php" method="get">
        <input id="search-bar" type="text" name="query" placeholder="Enter your search query...">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>

    <?php
    if (isset($_GET['query'])) {
        $query = $_GET['query'];
        // Connect to database ( replace with your own connection )
        $conn = new PDO('sqlite:search.db');

        // Prepare SQL query
        $stmt = $conn->prepare('SELECT * FROM table WHERE column LIKE :query');
        $stmt->bindParam(':query', '%' . $query . '%');
        $stmt->execute();

        // Fetch results
        $results = $stmt->fetchAll();

        // Display results
        if ($results) {
            echo '<h2>Search Results:</h2>';
            foreach ($results as $result) {
                echo '<p>' . $result['column'] . '</p>';
            }
        } else {
            echo '<p>No results found.</p>';
        }

        // Close database connection
        $conn = null;
    }
    ?>
</body>
</html>
```
**search.php**
```php
<?php
// Connect to database ( replace with your own connection )
$conn = new PDO('sqlite:search.db');

// Prepare SQL query
$query = $_GET['query'];
$stmt = $conn->prepare('SELECT * FROM table WHERE column LIKE :query');
$stmt->bindParam(':query', '%' . $query . '%');
$stmt->execute();

// Fetch results
$results = $stmt->fetchAll();

// Display results
if ($results) {
    echo '<h2>Search Results:</h2>';
    foreach ($results as $result) {
        echo '<p>' . $result['column'] . '</p>';
    }
} else {
    echo '<p>No results found.</p>';
}

// Close database connection
$conn = null;
?>
```
**Explanation**

* In the `index.php` file, we have a simple form with an input field and a submit button. When the user submits the form, it sends a GET request to the `search.php` file.
* The `search.php` file connects to a SQLite database ( replace with your own connection ) using PDO.
* We prepare a SQL query that searches for matching rows in the `table` table where the `column` column matches the search query. We use LIKE operator with wildcard (`%`) to match any characters before and after the search query.
* We fetch all results from the database using `$stmt->fetchAll()`.
* If there are results, we display them on the page; otherwise, we show a "No results found" message.

**Example Use Case**

Suppose you have a table called `books` with columns `title`, `author`, and `genre`. You want to create a search bar that searches for books by title. You can replace the placeholders in the code above with your own database connection and table/column names.

Remember to adjust the SQL query to match your specific database schema!

